Ongoing nausea, vomiting, and fevers to 107.1° F (41.7° C) prompted a positron emission tomography (PET) scan. Intense diffuse 18F-fluorodeoxyglucose uptake was noted in the liver (Figure 1
). Subsequent liver and bone marrow biopsies demonstrated numerous fibrin ring granulomas (Figures 2
and 3
), raising suspicion for Coxiella burnetii infection. Serologies confirmed the diagnosis of acute Q fever with phase I and phase II IgM and IgG titers > 256 on indirect immunofluorescence assay (Focus Diagnostics, Inc., Cypress, CA).
